[1
Date: Mon, 30 Nov 1998 10:18:50 +1000
From: Linda Selvey <SELVEYL@health.qld.gov.au>

In response to the Moderator's comments about the Australian Government
making JE vaccine available to all Australian children, the government has
not done so.  Rather it has created a funding mechanism by which
vaccination can be funded for children for whom vaccination has been
determined to be necessary.  At this point in time, only children living on
the outer islands of the Torres Strait will be vaccinated.
--
Linda Selvey
Manager, Communicable Diseases Unit
Queensland Health
Australia
e-mail: SELVEYL@health.qld.gov.au
[2
Date: Mon, 30 Nov 1998 17:00:59 +1100
From: Sonny Lau <melb@tmvc.com.au>

As far as I know, the routine JE vaccine is only offered to children in the
Torres Strait community, not to all Australian children. Please refer to
the following news script:
CANBERRA, Nov 10 AAP - The federal government was moving swiftly to ensure
children in the Torres Strait would be routinely vaccinated against
Japanese encephalitis (JE), federal health minister Dr Michael Wooldridge
said today. Opening a communicable diseases conference here, Dr Wooldridge
announced the JE vaccine would be added to the standard Australian
vaccination schedule. Four of Australia's five cases of JE occurred in the
islands and one was acquired on the mainland earlier this year. Dr
Wooldridge said the commonwealth's decision to fund vaccination provided a
mechanism to act quickly if JE became established in other areas of
Australia.
--
Dr. Sonny Lau
TMVC Melbourne
e-mail: melb@tmvc.com.au
