[3
Date: Sat, 28 Nov 1998 11:56:15 +1000
From: Jeffrey Hanna <MD1@health.qld.gov.au>

The Australian Minister for Health recently announced that the Commonwealth
would fund JE vaccination for children in communities considered to be
at-risk of JE by the relevant State or Territory public health authorities.
At the moment, the only communities considered to be at an on-going risk of
JE are those in the outer islands of the Torres Strait (see map Med J Aust
1996, 165:257).
A mass JE vaccination campaign took place in the outer islands in late
1995/early 1996. In that campaign 88% of the ~3500 residents received three
doses of JE vaccine (Comm Dis Intell 1996, 20:188-190). Since then, JE
vaccine has been integrated into the routine childhood immunisation
schedule in the outer islands, with the first dose being given with MMR at
12 months of age, the second a week later with the third (and final) dose
of Hib vaccine (PRP-OMP) and the third at 13 months of age. A booster dose
of JE vaccine was recently given to all those in the outer islands who
received their initial series in 1995/96. This dose was given therefore
about three years after the primary series, in anticipation of the 1998/99
wet season (which has just begun). About 2,000 doses were administered; no
concerning adverse reactions were reported.
Apart from in the outer islands of the Torres Strait, JE vaccine is
occasionally administered to Australians heading off to JE endemic
countries abroad.
In summary, JE vaccine is not being administered to Australians other than
those in the remote outer islands of the Torres Strait, and [to the
occasional traveller.
--
Dr Jeffrey Hanna
Public Health Physician
Tropical Public Health Unit
